Feature: bc-container inject commits the prompt to the in-container agent by issuing two discrete tmux send-keys invocations against the container driver — a text-only invocation followed by an Enter-only invocation

  Supersedes scenario 28 (features/bc-launcher/28-inject-submits-prompt-autonomously.gherkin). The Implementer must locate the BC-side hash of scenario 28 in the shopsystem-bc-launcher feature surface and retire that hash when landing this scenario.

  Scenario 28 pinned the user-meaningful behavior ("the agent processes the inject without further input") in terms of the agent's input-loop state, but that pin was satisfied by a single tmux send-keys invocation carrying both the prompt text and the Enter key as discrete argv elements — the same empirically-buggy shape that defeated scenario 27's pin on the launch path. The inject path on bc-launcher's controller.py exhibits the identical bug for the identical reason (tmux concatenates the multi-argv keystream into one pty write(); Claude Code's TUI absorbs the trailing CR into its input buffer rather than treating it as a submit keypress) and the identical fix applies (two separate send-keys invocations produce two discrete pty write() syscalls that the TUI processes as a discrete keypress event).

  This scenario re-grounds the inject-path pin from "the prompt is committed" (which the single-invocation shape spuriously satisfies in the testing layer) to "the BC issues two discrete tmux send-keys invocations against the container driver, in order: a text-only invocation carrying the prompt text and no Enter token, followed by an Enter-only invocation carrying the Enter token and no prompt text". The driver-surface assertion turns red under any single-invocation shape, catching any future regression at the BC's contract surface without requiring a live TUI. The inject-path pin is symmetric with the launch-path pin in scenario 30; the two together close the parallel inject-side bug tracked under lead-hyee.

  Scenario: bc-container inject issues two discrete tmux send-keys invocations against the container driver — first the prompt text alone, then the Enter key alone — and no single invocation carries both
    Given the shopsystem-bc-launcher BC is installed
    And a Docker container named "bc-shopsystem-messaging" is running with a tmux session named "agent"
    When I run "bc-container inject shopsystem-messaging 'bd prime'" and the command exits zero
    Then the BC has issued exactly two tmux send-keys invocations against the container driver targeting the tmux session named "agent" in container "bc-shopsystem-messaging" as a direct consequence of the inject command
    And the first of those two invocations carries the prompt text "bd prime" as its key payload and does not carry the Enter key in the same invocation
    And the second of those two invocations carries the Enter key as its key payload and does not carry the prompt text "bd prime" in the same invocation
    And no single tmux send-keys invocation issued by the inject command carries both the prompt text "bd prime" and the Enter key together
    And the two invocations are issued in order: the text-only invocation first, the Enter-only invocation second
